Problem Statement 1

The lack of health insurance coverage is a significant barrier to essential healthcare services, with approximately 1 in 10 individuals in the United States remaining uninsured. Although Medicaid provides healthcare access to many low-income Americans, some states are declining to expand the program, despite the expansion's aim to include more individuals. In 2014, Medicaid enrollment was 53 million in expansion states and 17 million in non-expansion states. By 2020, enrollment figures reached 61 Million for adopted states and 19 Million for non-adopted states. This disparity in Medicaid expansion hinders progress towards a healthier nation by limiting affordable healthcare coverage for individuals. To gain insights into the potential benefits of expanding the program, it is crucial to utilize the Tableau reporting tool to analyze state health reports, insurance trends, and underlying causes of death from 2015 to 2020.
